{"Category": "History, Humanities, Religion", "End Date": "", "Name": "Liberal Modernity: the War within Islam", "URL": "https://www.smith.edu/about-smith/new-calendar?trumbaEmbed=view%3Devent%26eventid%3D279851360", "Location": "Smith College, Northampton, MA", "Time": "5:00-6:30pm", "Date": "Thu, Mar 22, 2018", "Organization": "Smith College", "Emily: \ud83d\udc4d": "", "Description": "Since Albert Hourani\u2019s publication of Arabic Thought in the Liberal Age (1962), the historiography of Arab-Islamic thought has been defined in reference to the liberal framework. Liberalism has been employed to identify the dynamics within Islamic thought and distinguish between \u201cmoderate,\u201d \u201cconservative\u201d and \u201cextremist\u201d Islams. In this context, historians have engaged with \u201cIslam and liberalism\u201d, \u201cIslam in liberalism\u201d, and \u201cIslam after liberalism.\u201d But is there an Islam without liberalism?\nProf. Ghazal\u2019s talk examines a strand of religious thought during the \u201cliberal age\u201d that refused to accept the premises of liberalism, did not define Islam in relationship to it, and, more importantly, defended Islam against it. The proponents of this thought understood liberalism not only as championing social, cultural and religious values menacing to Islam and Muslims, but also as a political project aimed to destroy Islam. For them, liberalism embodied the battle between Christianity and Islam, and that between Europe and the Ottoman Empire. Therefore, they considered those Muslim modernists who promoted liberalism as traitors to Islam and facilitators of colonial projects. The Sufi scholar Yusuf al-Nabhani (1849\u20131932) best articulated these views. The lecture also addresses the polemics between al-Nabhani and Wahhabis who shared his disdain for liberalism. With the relative eclipse of Sufism in the Arab world in the 20th century and the eventual rise of Wahhabism, the battle to defend Islam against liberalism was largely left to the Wahhabis. The lecture concludes by suggesting that there is an intellectual genealogy linking al-Nabhani and his Wahhabi counterparts to a group like ISIS in its deliberate attempt to define and portray Islam as being opposed to values associated with liberalism.\nAmal Ghazal is Associate Professor of History & Director of the Center for Comparative Study of Muslim Societies and Cultures at Simon Fraser University. She is a known specialist on modern Islamic reform movements. "},
